node.text: Thats an ancient study. Please do your astral map, you will be very grateful :) metaphysical science is indeed finally something in 2025!
Jung didn't believe and yet found it useful. I think that "believe" is not the best word you could have picked there, I too could use it as "not the best mirror" yet without any beliving involved
#astrology #nononsensespirituality
@nononsensespirituality and just because apologists justification sounds like astrology apologetics - if there’s such a thing- it doesn’t mean it applies just the same either
@gclefm really? It’s incredibly complex actually. That’s 5,000 years of history in itself with an incredible amount of nuance.
@gclefm you don’t think it’s curious that everyone is using the same arguments and tricks for their religions and new age spirituality and yet they all can’t be true? I find that curious.
Astrology is the study of patterns and its recognition. Some use it as a religious belief but that’s not what it’s intended for. You can’t say a pattern isn’t true. It just is.

This is incredibly unkind. I am a huge advocate for feminine spirituality, as a speaker, coach, and plant medicine guide for women. Because I disagree with you I am just a parrot for white men or here for clicks? Let me tell you this. I wish I was wrong. I make little money in my grounded approach to spirituality. I’d make far more money doing readings for people. That would actually be the way to engage people if that were my goal. One of the best things I can do for women and queer people is highlight tools that help while also being aware of the shadow side of intuition. Intuition without rationality has dangers. As a woman I will never again participate in a spiritual path that tells me to turn part of me off or kill a part of me to participate. And some astrologers do ask me to have faith and turn off my brain. Im not against using this as a tool, but as you can see in my comment section, people are treating this like a religion and doing a lot of spiritual bypassing with it. It’s kindness to show not only the best of the feminine but also its shadow. Otherwise we’re no better than men who don’t see their shadow in their dependence on rationality.
@nononsensespirituality Astrology has absolutely no scientific basis. To condem rationality, reason and critical thought is irresponsible.

@ljsall3 I’ve never done that. I’ll never leave rationality at the door. But let’s not pretend that our entire brain is rational. We are also experiencing creatures because consciousness has an experiential quality.

Hmm.. I appreciate the confidence in your voice, but your remarkable ignorance is showing. After observing you more you seem like someone who once lacking expertise somewhere, needs to overtake that topic to denounce it. Anyway, history lesson. Without Astrology, no one would be here. Farmers wouldn’t have been able to get us here without tracking the moon cycles to grow crops. CC: the 1800s. They still use Astrology btw. And there’s a lot more where that came from. Scientific studies show that biological women cycle with the new and full moon cycles more often than any other periods. Conclusive, repeatable studies cannot be done on Astrology for the most BEAUTIFUL and cosmic reason that is meant to surpass your (and everyone’s) comprehension, and that is this: Every planet will never be in the same exact location again as it once was, ever. Timing is divine. Timing is everything. Women feel time in our bodies as part of our inherent intuition. Astrology comes from the original myths. Astrology gave us our first archetypes. A talented astrologer, Carl Jung, gave us the word archetypes. Johannes Kepler, another talented astrologer, gave us the heliocentric model. Furthermore, few “studies” have been done on Astrology. But I would LOVE to list some patterns for you of historical events that have taken place due to the same transits repeating. My fear is that you’ll delete my comment because your ego will feel more important than the usefulness of this information. But I will continue. Richard Tarnas predicted Covid as part of the 2020 Jupiter Saturn and Pluto conjunctions. You would be amazed at the predictions Astrologers have made and continue to make. You would be amazed at the current transit history repeating right now this second. But your curiosity and yearning for spiritual development would have to be bigger than your ego’s yearning for authority on the public stage. Feel free to lmk if you want my full dissertation. I would love to tell you about the women Astrologers contributions and those who were stolen from, of which were written out intentionally, just like women……

@nononsensespirituality I do organize regularly, perhaps professionally, but not at the same depth or randomness as I do unknowingly during Mercury retrograde. Certain tasks—like a full garage reorganization—naturally align with these periods, which then help me be more practical in my day-to-day life. Just like the moon cycles shift the tides, there are countless examples of energetic syncs influencing nature and behavior. Whether we actively track them or not, these patterns exist.
@thirdeyebroad patterns are fine to live by, but were the ones making the patterns meaningful.

@nononsensespirituality Yes, we engage with patterns and interpret them—but does that mean we create them, or are we just recognizing something that already exists? The moon doesn’t need us to believe in its influence to shift the tides. Birds don’t need us to assign meaning to migration patterns for them to follow natural cycles. Just because something requires perception to be understood doesn’t mean it only exists in our minds.

You can’t blame being late on Mercury retrograde—you have to recognize that this period brings a higher likelihood of inconvenient disruptions, which means being more prepared is essential. However, the challenge is that Mercury retrograde tends to drain our energy, making that extra preparation feel even more demanding. This forces us to work smarter, not harder, and to reassess how we manage our time and resources.

Once again, the simplified, pop-culture version of astrology barely scratches the surface of real, in-depth astrology. Some people actually thrive during Mercury retrograde, especially if they were born during one or have a chart that aligns well with its energy. They may even find themselves feeling clearer and more focused during this time.

Mercury retrograde is an opportunity to reassess, reevaluate, and reconsider what’s truly productive and necessary in your life. Interestingly, I don’t even check when Mercury retrograde is happening, yet every single time, I find myself naturally reorganizing or restructuring things. Whether we realize it or not, we move in sync with these energetic cycles.

That’s actually why science tests against placebo so that it remains objective, science can only be interpreted with more science. Otherwise our brains make the assessment and decides on its own based on what we’ve previously known and understood, we only know what we know.

@nononsensespirituality The difference is that astrology isn’t a religion—it doesn’t require blind faith or divine authority. It’s a system of pattern recognition that has been studied, adapted, and applied in many cultures. Dismissing it outright while favoring Enneagrams (which also rely on pattern interpretation) is selective reasoning. If meaning-making from patterns is invalid, then wouldn’t that apply to personality models as well?

@whered_zoedream you not @nononsensespirituality know enough about Astrology to speak to it. If you want to take your own years long intensives, studying under mentors, and report back with your own genuine documented research, we will be all ears. Until then, let’s keep quiet about where we don’t hold expertise. Thank you.

When someone presents themselves as the ultimate authority on ‘truth’—especially in areas where objective proof is impossible—they end up creating just another belief system. It’s one thing to share opinions or personal insights, but when they attack others (like astrology) while treating their own views as unquestionable, it becomes hypocritical.

She dismisses ideas she doesn’t personally believe in while expecting others to accept her claims as fact. That’s no different from religious fundamentalism—just under a different label. In reality, no belief system can be absolutely proven, and all sources can be questioned, making her just another person pushing subjective beliefs as universal truth.

That said, actual astrology—not just the generalized, pop-culture version, but real, in-depth astrology—has proven itself through history and personal experience. It serves as an energy forecasting tool that not only aids in self-reflection but also assists in planning. Like science, astrology can be interpreted in multiple ways; dismissing it outright would be like claiming meteorology isn’t real just because weather predictions aren’t always exact
@maxrohleder they’re about to get real loud here
I learned on your posts that there are still people who really follow astrology
@bloomapotheca a huge shit 😭😭🤣 a huge shift*

@bloomapotheca I myself prefer tools where there it’s harder to “miss the point” just because I’ve seen so many have regrets on that path. But for those who genuinely use it as a tool, I have no quarrel.
@nononsensespirituality interesting! I’m curious how you feel about energy work! Have you ever tried anything like that?

Is your intention to throw away the whole tool because YOU couldn’t or didn’t want to use it as a threshold the way some other people do? Genuinely curious. Because for me, astrology was one of some AMAZING tools that were the gateway into my interest in embarking on a spiritual journey and really my personal healing journey in the first place. 

I feel like that’s what much of the whole witchy/spiritual aesthetic has been over the last several years. People on the threshold of pushing truly inward, and I’ve seen a huge shit in consciousness these last few months. In myself even, too. Are these tools not valuable because some people get caught up in them and miss the fact that they are merely TOOLS for consciousness?
@annam.art Science *is* already questioned. By scientists. Constantly. That's their job.

@stevepayne1972 look around you , there is lot of mess on this planet and science unfortunately has created . Have you also noticed how many times science got it wrong and then they have to go back to cleaning up the mess they created while we believe them unquestionably. Astrology is a science , it’s not the weekly horoscope . Anyone who has not studied it dies not have the authority to belittle it . If an individual chooses not to believe in something it does not mean it doesn’t exist or is not true . Only arrogance and ignorance makes it so

@annam.art you missed the point. Science is the only thing that humans do that self corrects. Religion does not. Astrology does not. The fact that science messes up and changes is a great thing. No matter how complex you make astrology, and I’ll admit it gets incredibly complex, that does not validate the base truth claims being made by astrology, that celestial bodies affect humans, or that patterns are anything more than hindsight bias.

Have you studied astrology ? 
In today’s day and age we need to start questioning science and stop relying so much on their truth . 
Astrology is Annan ancient tool of wisdom . Science or Meta wouldn’t even have a clue on what that means !
@goofy_enfriends if the truth claims don’t matter you can actually do the same work no matter your sign.

@goofy_enfriends I fully agree with what you’re saying and it’s clear to me that although this person has shared a lot of wisdom that I’ve appreciated, their grasp of astrology is extremely limited at best. 

The algo showed me another  video right before this one that does an excellent job of refuting points just like this one: https://www.instagram.com/reel/DEyex0fMZJQ/?igsh=MWVvcTZhM3loZjl2bg==

@goofy_enfriends that is true, even her belief in that humans have no free will is debatable. I was reading differeint neuroscientists takes on it and there is a whole lot that goes into that argument along with behavior scientists, philosophers, biology, psychology. It's definitely not a layered topic, its definitely not black and white. Getting into reading the science behind that thinking is that I simply don't agree with it after listenging to interviews with neuroscientists about it. One researcher Robert Sapolsky makes that claim but also Sapolksy suffers from depression too and has for a while so it makes me wonder does that influence his outlook?

Science is constantly evolving and just because we do not yet have the technology to prove something using the scientific method doesn’t mean it’s invalid. Don’t get me wrong- if there’s science that asserts something is doing more harm than it is good I trust science. But just because science can’t prove something’s legitimacy doesn’t mean we should disregard it. I love acupuncture which was not developed using the scientific method. It’s been used for many, many generations but for most of its existence there was no scientific evidence to prove its efficacy or how it works. Because of this so many people have called it a gimmick and denied there’s any actual healing happening so people who use it are just wasting their money. However, in just the past ten years or so scientists have developed ways to measure how frequencies travel through the human body and all of their findings have backed up the acupuncture theories. Just because we aren’t there yet doesn’t mean science won’t someday back up astrology. Science certainly hasn’t disproved it. Many people who believe in science also embrace astrology and I’ve seen astrologers accurately predict a crazy amount of things. I’ve also had experiences that repeatedly coincide with the same astrological events (many of which I wasn’t even aware of at the time of the happenings, I only connected the dots afterwards so I don’t think I was just projecting these things to happen). No one has to follow astrology if they don’t want to and I agree many people overthink it but I embrace astrology to a certain degree and there’s nothing wrong with that. I think it’s far more systematic and rooted in things we directly experience than most religious doctrines are.

In wisdom traditions, especially those of the east, one would proffer “pointing out” instructions in response to your position.  Pointing Out instructions allow the person holding the bias to see the reflection they are perceiving contains within it the bias they themselves hold.

You can see why non-dualists and quantum scientists get along.  A razor cannot cut itself.  And these comments are your razor.
